# Administrator Group Modification Detection

## Objective

Detect when a user account is added to the local Administrators group.

---

## Overview

This analytics rule monitors Windows Security Event ID **4732**, which records changes to local security-enabled groups.

---

## Severity

High

---

## MITRE ATT&CK

| Tactic | Technique | Technique ID |
|----------|-----------|--------------|
| Privilege Escalation | Account Manipulation | T1098 |

---

## Data Source

- Windows Security Event Logs
- Azure Monitor Agent
- Azure Arc
- Log Analytics Workspace

---

## Detection Logic

Whenever a user is added to the Administrators group, Event ID 4732 is generated and Microsoft Sentinel creates an alert.

---

## KQL Query

```kql
Event
| where EventID == 4732
| project TimeGenerated, Computer, RenderedDescription
```

---

## Test Performed

Executed:

```cmd
net localgroup Administrators hacker /add
```

Verified Event ID 4732 in Log Analytics.

---

## Expected Alert

User Added to Administrators Group

---

## Investigation Steps

1. Identify the modified group.
2. Determine which user was added.
3. Verify who performed the action.
4. Confirm change approval.
5. Investigate additional privilege escalation activity.

---

## Recommended Response

- Remove unauthorized accounts.
- Review administrative actions.
- Reset privileged credentials if necessary.
- Investigate possible compromise.

---

## Lessons Learned

Unexpected administrator group modifications are high-risk events that may indicate privilege escalation by an attacker.
